  "teachingObjective": "Child can spell words with the prefix un- and knows it means 'not' or 'opposite of'.",
  "childFriendlyExplanation": "un- is a tiny part that means NOT or the OPPOSITE. Stick it on the front and the word flips: kind → unkind, lock → unlock. The base word keeps every letter.",
  "ruleExplanation": "un- is always spelled u-n, attached before a base word whose spelling stays the same: un + happy = unhappy, un + necessary = unnecessary (double n stays).",
  "watchForCue": "un- is always just u-n, and the base keeps all its letters — even if that makes nn.",
  "anchorWord": "unhappy",
